 {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 1995\u20132000\n|rank          = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|18px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit          = [[214th Fires Brigade (United States)|214th Fires Brigade]]\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Alexander Garrett Jr.''' (born March 27, 1972) is an American politician and former [[prosecutor]]. He is the [[United States Representative]] for [[Virginia's 5th congressional district]].  A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Garrett formerly represented the [[Virginia Senate, District 22|22nd District]] in the [[Virginia Senate]].<ref name=\"Rohr\" />\n\n==Early life and family==\nThomas Garrett was born in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], to Thomas Alexander Garrett Sr. and his wife, Lois. Garrett is a graduate of [[Louisa County High School]] and earned his undergraduate and law degrees from the [[University of Richmond]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Garrett to Challenge Short for Louisa Post |newspaper=[[The Central Virginian]] |date=June 21, 2007}}</ref>  He resides with his wife, Flanna, and three daughters, Carolyn, Laura and Locke in unincorporated [[Buckingham County, Virginia|Buckingham County]] (with a [[Scottsville, Virginia|Scottsville]] address).\n\n==Military career==\nGarrett served for six years in the [[U.S. Army]],<ref>Staff reports, [http://www.yourgv.com/news/local_news/candidates-for-th-district-outline-priorities-for-southside/article_523c6818-9edd-11e6-abba-6bc4fac378e4.html Candidates for 5th District outline priorities for Southside], ''Gazette-Virginian'' (October 31, 2016).</ref> where he was a Field Artillery Officer.<ref>James Ivancic, [http://www.fauquier.com/news/freshman-congressman-tom-garrett-looks-forward-to-busy-session/article_088bfd74-cbff-11e6-b75c-5b470d6cecaf.html Freshman Congressman Tom Garrett looks forward to busy session], ''Fauquier Times'' (December 27, 2016).</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Commonwealth's attorney===\nGarrett served as an Assistant Attorney General under Virginia Attorney General [[Bob McDonnell]]. In 2007, he was elected [[Commonwealth's Attorney]] for [[Louisa County, Virginia|Louisa County]].\n\n===State Senate===\nAfter the [[Virginia General Assembly|General Assembly]] redistricted the State Senate as required by the Virginia Constitution in 2011, Garrett decided to run in an open seat. The 22nd District was open due to the incumbent Republican [[Ralph K. Smith]]'s home in [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]] being drawn into another district.\n\nIn the Republican primary, Garrett came in first in a five-person field with nearly 26% of the vote and a margin of fewer than 200 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voterinfo.sbe.virginia.gov/election/DATA/2011/EB178FD6-875D-4B0D-A295-900A0482F523/Unofficial/7_p1_s.shtml|title=2011 Results, Virginia State Board of Elections|publisher=|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>  During his time in office, he served on the General Laws and Technology, Courts of Justice, Education and Health, and Privileges and Elections committees.\n\n===2016 congressional election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2016#District 5}}\nIn May 2016, after three ballots at the [[Republican Party of Virginia convention, 2016|Republican nominating convention]], Garrett won the Republican nomination for [[U.S. Representative]] in [[Virginia's 5th congressional district]].<ref name=\"Rohr\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsadvance.com/news/local/sen-tom-garrett-wins-th-district-republican-nomination-on-third/article_47d80a04-19f3-11e6-b9c8-1b0471aae5f8.html|title=Sen. Tom Garrett wins 5th District Republican nomination on third ballot|last=Rohr|first=Alex|date=May 14, 2016|newspaper=[[The News & Advance]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 2016 general election, Garrett defeated Democratic nominee Jane Dittmar, the former chairwoman of the [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle County]] board of supervisors. Garrett won with 58.2% of the vote to Dittmar's 41.6%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wtop.com/virginia/2016/11/virginia-2016-general-election-results/#house|title=Virginia 2016 general election results|date=November 9, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://historical.elections.virginia.gov/elections/search/year_from:2016/year_to:2016/office_id:5/district_id:27258|title=Virginia Elections Database \u00bb Search Elections|website=Virginia Elections Database|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===115th Congress===\nIn January 2017,  Garrett was named to the House Committees on Foreign Affairs, Homeland Security, and Education and the Workforce. He is also a member of the conservative [[House Freedom Caucus]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/three-virginia-gop-congressmen-including-rep-tom-garrett-in-th/article_381db19e-3a89-5e45-8c4f-83f2f65b8396.html |title=Three Virginia GOP congressmen, including Rep. Tom Garrett in 5th District, line up against GOP health care plan |newspaper=The Roanoke Times |first=Jenna |last=Portnoy |date=March 15, 2017 |access-date=February 7, 2018 }}</ref> though he told voters during the campaign that he would not join the hard right group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsadvance.com/opinion/editorials/an-endorsement-garrett-would-fight-for-fifth-district-in-congress/article_e28c347c-9fa3-11e6-875d-1f9ca5c244d0.html|title=An Endorsement: Garrett Would Fight for Fifth District in Congress|last=BOARD|first=THE EDITORIAL|work=NewsAdvance.com|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> Garrett is a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 re-election campaign===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2018#District 5}}\nIn the spring of 2018, reports surfaced that Garrett might not seek re-election after his second chief of staff resigned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/23/tom-garrett-chief-of-staff-605668|title=Garrett in turmoil, might quit Congress|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/virginia_politics/report-garrett-might-drop-out-of-th-district-race/article_7db0fd56-5ecb-11e8-a6da-d732ad6b2a0e.html|title=Report: Garrett might drop out of 5th District race|last=Hammel|first=Tyler|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> Garrett clarified later that he intended to run<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/garrett-says-he-will-run-for-reelection/article_1aa92e7c-5f7f-11e8-b9f4-fb01f5a0da8a.html|title=Garrett says he will run for reelection|last=reports|first=The Daily Progress staff|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> in what long-time political analyst [[Larry Sabato]] called \"one of the oddest\" speeches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/LarrySabato/status/999708066479267841|title=Larry Sabato on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> As of April 2018, Garrett was outraised by multiple Democratic opponents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/19/house-republicans-fundraising-2018-midterms-493823|title=Democrats crush House Republicans in fundraising|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> In light of these fundraising numbers, the [[The Cook Political Report|Cook Political Report]] moved the race from \"likely Republican\" to the more competitive \"leans Republican.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cookpolitical.com/analysis/house/house-overview/new-house-fec-reports-rating-changes-7-districts|title=New House FEC Reports: Rating Changes in 7 Districts|work=The Cook Political Report|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> Democrats went on to nominate former investigative journalist [[Leslie Cockburn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/cockburn-receives-th-district-democratic-nomination/article_f5e08b44-9431-5303-8224-4dc49dc02910.html|title=Cockburn receives 5th District Democratic nomination|last=Progress|first=Tyler Hammel The (Charlottesville) Daily|work=Roanoke Times|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 former staffers told ''[[Politico]]'' that Garrett and his wife often assigned them tasks \"that were unofficial and personal in nature\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-aides say congressman made them his servants|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/25/tom-garrett-staff-servants-608665|website=[[Politico]]|date=May 25, 2018|accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> On May 28, 2018, Garrett announced that he is an alcoholic and said he wouldn't seek reelection to his seat in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2018|2018 elections]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Washington Post |title=Rep. Garrett announces he is an alcoholic and will not seek re-election. |accessdate=May 28, 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/rep-garrett-announces-he-is-an-alcoholic-and-will-not-seek-re-election/2018/05/28/40e8839a-62b2-11e8-99d2-0d678ec08c2f_story.html?noredirect=on}}</ref>\n\n== Jason Kessler Controversy ==\n\nIn March 2017, Garrett posed for a photo with [[Jason Kessler]], one of his constituents who was an organizer of the [[Unite the Right rally|Unite the Right]] rally, a [[far-right]] rally held in August 2017 in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]]. The rally became the site of violent clashes leaving about 30 people injured, followed shortly by an incident in which a white supremacist [[vehicle ramming attack|rammed his car]] into a crowd, killing a woman and injuring another 19 other people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/how-virginia-candidates-responded-to-the-white-nationalist-rally-in-charlottesville/2017/08/12/8b634be6-7f85-11e7-83c7-5bd5460f0d7e_story.html|title=How Virginia candidates responded to the white nationalist rally in Charlottesville|website=[[Washington Post]]|date=August 12, 2017|access-date=2017-08-31}}</ref> Following the violence at the rally, Garrett disavowed the organizer and said he was unaware of Kessler's role in the rally when they initially met.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://tomgarrett.house.gov/ Congressman Thomas Garrett Jr.] official U.S. House website\n* [https://www.tomgarrettforcongress.com Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Virginia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Thomas_Garrett_%5BR-5%5D|Tom Garrett}}\n* {{C-SPAN|tomgarrett}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-va-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ralph K. Smith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Virginia Senate]]<br>from the [[Virginia Senate, District 22|22nd]] district|years=2012\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Peake]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Virginia\n| district=5\n| before=[[Robert Hurt (politician)|Robert Hurt]]\n| start=2017\n}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Gallagher (U.S. legislator)|Mike Gallagher]]<br>R-[[Wisconsin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=390th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vicente Gonz\u00e1lez (politician)|Vicente Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br>D-[[Texas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{VA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, Tom}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:County and city Commonwealth's Attorneys in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Louisa County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n